tasks.task: Starting vegetable seeds indoors in February
subtasks: Gather supplies
Fill seed trays with high-quality seed starting mix
Plant tomato seeds a quarter-inch deep
Place seed trays in bright window or with grow lights
Ensure consistent moisture
Provide tomatoes with six hours of sunlight per day after sprouting
Use grow lights for 12-16 hours a day
Gradually acclimate tomato seedlings to outdoor conditions
Plant pepper seeds a quarter-inch deep
Maintain temperature around 70-80°F with grow lights
Brush seedlings with hand to strengthen stems
Provide consistent moisture for pepper seedlings
Plant eggplant seeds a quarter-inch deep
Maintain temperature around 75°F with heating mat
Ensure plenty of bright, indirect sunlight for eggplants
Sow broccoli seeds half-inch deep
Maintain temperature between 60-65°F for broccoli seedlings
Keep soil consistently moist for broccoli
Check for pests and diseases in broccoli seedlings
Transplant broccoli outdoors when danger of frost passes
Sow cauliflower seeds half-inch deep
Maintain cooler temperature (60-65°F) for cauliflower seedlings
Keep soil consistently moist for cauliflower
Start lettuce seeds a quarter-inch deep
Maintain temperature around 60-70°F for lettuce
Provide bright indirect light for lettuce
Start spinach seeds a half-inch deep
Keep temperature between 60-70°F for spinach seedlings
Provide bright indirect light for spinach
Start kale seeds a half-inch deep
Keep temperature between 60-70°F for kale
Provide bright indirect light for kale
Wait for seedling emergence and adjust care as needed
